This paper is likely to belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it deals with semantic segmentation, a popular computer vision task. The paper also proposes a novel architecture for this task, which suggests a focus on the development of computer vision models. 

The paper may also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category as it involves the development of a deep learning model for semantic segmentation. 

The paper's focus on generating visual representations from semantic word embeddings suggests that it may also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category, which often deals with natural language processing and machine learning. 

The paper's use of self-training and automatic pseudo-labeling suggests a focus on improving model performance, which could place it in the Computational Linguistics (cs.CL) sub-category, which often deals with improving natural language processing models. 

Finally, the paper's use of graph-context encoding to leverage spatial context priors suggests a focus on neural networks and their applications, which could place it in the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
